The first virtual operator is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is well developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long before we get there.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive of the Union.
After the final steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competence that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and its high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
That is why the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a sharp drop in prices to which the classic operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into Britain's market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the Virtual Mobilking Operator in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator achieved more than 100,000 customers and became the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they are enough with many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, often counteracts the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of the price compared to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland can also be a good blow the bet by a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could be stuck in our country.
From this the spokesman of Vodafone, Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it's about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in a phone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly he assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition emerges.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it the Group GTS Novera who would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in it, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And how much sooner, better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said Pavel Kaidl, the group spokesperson.
So, maybe they're better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would have to reach possibly by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this point we believe that the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far, no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said mobil.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market concerns other operators.
T-mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "Even today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be hard to find some virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study on such a short horizon"
Vodafone directs your attention rather to the fulfilment of the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this is about spending and infrastructure sharing.
We think of it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - with operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thus a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry to competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to ČTú was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile society.
Public information available on ČTú's ČTú websites is a testimony to this.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would imply for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously disappointing because of the absolute disregard of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just about ČTU's position, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This purely belongs to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator is closed.
To date, no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of operators.
For the offices that should represent the interests of consumers, it is something more than a consideration, besides that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In the overseas where virtual operators work normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile phone services"
Of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and price reductions does not fall within the interest of UOHS.
Really the dramatically shocking in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in petrol stations because it is clear that it is a work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found any sign of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding rise of responsibility in their market operations.
The tools needed to open up the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," added Chalupa's response.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many conflicting points.
Clearly there is a relevant market analysis developed by ČTU that telecommunications is from the point of view of the commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise sharply in a similar manner.
Current complaints from stakeholders (induced by the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators they are shocked by many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in ČTú is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act was recently introduced for the extension of ČTU's competition in the field of trade tenders which was not implemented, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known by UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one's looking
At the same time, unprecedentably something like a pseudovirtual operator that on Czech mobile telephony networks already exist a few.
They are companies that place their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephony services.
Normally only some elected ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is in which the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of it ordering a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will later receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those quoted could be discovered, we could talk about a breach in the terms of contract that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given society," answered Martina Kemrová's question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies cited that it can come to be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get a profit that is not negligible and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of the possible problems: "The law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a demeanable so many customers.
These, moreover, must accept that the SIM card of your phone is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of operators."
This is exactly what should seem to the ČTU minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it must not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that its commercial conditions do not allow it.
When are we going to stop being the most expensive?
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this disruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases defended operators but their clients.
Outside with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and with it others began to appear.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience, we cannot help but be impressed by the confusion of the powers in these cases.
But do not despair.
If this information between the backs is correct and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market probably starts moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile telephony operator enter, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may no longer call more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations from the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and another female voice, one with Coro and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are spoken of as singing.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can hear the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it has intentionally chosen for the Solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with the two and then, too, with the Choir that were fixed in the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates next year on 175th anniversary.
The song Where, my Home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
