The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated his 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public's confidence that it had been seriously vacillated by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada made a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, says Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence " , says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, about 94 per cent of the Quebec population had in successive confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary nevertheless recalls that " trust is something extremely fragile " .
Since its inception, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended the birth in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious illness can emerge from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But some years ago, it has been shown out of all doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that enable the presence of the virus and not of antibodies against the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, in which the evidence used so far was based.
Nuclid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the moment the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We could reduce this period by less than a week.
We have thus substantially reduced the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means you will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of HIV transmission occurs for a blood product.
I believe that today one can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries," says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It's never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant " , Dr. Décary pursues before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
" Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since the most aggressive anti-carcinogenic treatments, patients often need injections of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors regrouping only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation on an average basis. "
All persons with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria may still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
Pancy is very rare.
But members of this donor network have to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to convince people to give their blood, but above all, to hold them back and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," is plagued Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Québec not only supplies blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical wastes is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord-blooding program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this, since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
