Superposition Psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are prone to spend more money and overvalue the product.
The neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose on competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and while the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of self-premium of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups waged against a person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members were betting.
The other group was promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the members of the group lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation" - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York, established.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
In the world, some five million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and disease are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are propagated by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with contaminated water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sembling, vagina mood, saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be protected by vaccines against A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, is manifested by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that they appear in the skin and in the white of the eyes the jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the dark-colored urine and the healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected patients receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent destroys liver cells in palatine form and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control is therefore very important.
This disease is much more frequent in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control, it is worth consulting with the family doctor by experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease is cured if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the body virus, so it can be suppressed the infection and prevent cancer.
On 30 September, the World Day of Hepatitis was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less who they believe in God?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith has a soothing effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
The Oxford University scientists had an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain - the British Telegraph reported.
In the framework of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it could be verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of research in which, alongside academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians also participate in the different departments of the University.
The analysis occurred in the following way; they fixed a chipping instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electrical shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to set their eyes on two paintings; to the Virgin Mary, work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and to the Lady of the Armiño of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious theme painting or the other.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safety" as people "protected," they "resolved themselves and peace reigned in their hearts."
As they observed the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person who feels very positively, like a mother or father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on pain regulation if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
