The smart car imitates the flight of the suburb
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, but to imitate the sensors of obstacles in nature?
For example, that of the suburbs.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the beekeepers gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic management system of cars type BR23C mimicking nature, to which they gave the characteristics of the benefactors, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all the collisions.
During the flight each bee creates its own ovaled private space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
An important role is played by the eyes composed of the benefactors that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser-ray length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to prevent collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the alleys, changes the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system at present, this manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," says Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what one beeper does to dodge other beehouses.
This process must be done in an open and close the eyes.
However, unlike the binoculars, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonals, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the beehouses to dodge other beeholes, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and acceleration in addition the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is higher, which means they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, not much less the storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There's no need for gigabytes, no megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles on his way.
