The written version of the $700 billion financial ransom package law has been prepared to be applied in several stages in order to buy bank credit.
In the first phase half of the money will be spent.
According to hours on the east coast during the new consultations that lasted until midnight on Saturday, the conference leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial rescue package in total, after several days of discussion - Reuters reported.
We have achieved an important progress - said Nancy Pelossi, Democratic President of the North American Congress, claiming that the agreement is only needed to be formalized in a document.
The commitment made to the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the commitment stated: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelossi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning it back into the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 p.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular leap in the bags.
On the draft law called an emergency law for the economic stabilization of 2008, Monday will first vote on the North American Congress and then on the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelossi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress made during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the spokesman for the White House.
The program is different from the original Bush administration proposal to spend all 700 billion dollars to buy bad credit fund securities.
Only half of the $700 billion will now be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, the Ministry of Finance will purchase securities of credit funds, of poor rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the decision of the President.
This programme will be controlled by a special agency, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion may be spent after a new Congress decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can buy at the same time bad credits, mortgages and credit fund securities, as well as other “vengeous” types credits as well.
Purchasing can be done in auctions or directly - informed competent persons in the ministry.
The law allows the affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson stated: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the US financial system, is dealing with the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the risk prevention that could lead to the demolition of some major financial institutions.
We do everything we can to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and are waiting for State aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the US argot simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain specific cases will payments be limited, in addition the limitations depend on the form of assistance from the Ministry of Finance.
Limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed for gold parachutes, unless the failed head of the bank retires.
By directly purchasing bad credits, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the compensation of heads is not overstated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations relate only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in American history that will be in force a legal limitation for the revenues of the directors general - said this measure the Democratic Barney Frank, chairman of the Congress commission, responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares from the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they will ultimately be able to obtain gains with the transaction as soon as the economy is recovered and with it the bank.
According to the bill for the next five years, the President will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return losses from the financial sector to taxpayers.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what American citizens have entrusted to us, that is, they are not protecting the dollars of taxpayers - declared the Republican Congressman of California, Darrell Issa.
His fellow-Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur said: the measures urged him the same as those responsible for the demolition of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month prices and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - the Central Statistics Office (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum extent, with 0.1 per cent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry rose by at least 0.1 per cent in July.
The largest increase in the volume of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to the increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and to an increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
A price decrease occurred in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a 12-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the determining weight food, beverages and tobacco industry there was an 11 per cent increase.
Price decreases in the textile industry (2.5 per cent) as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The electricity prices, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the previous year's prices by 18.7 per cent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate prices there was no change over the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods producing branches, a 6.8 per cent decrease was recorded, and in investment goods a 1.4 per cent decrease was recorded.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007, strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
