"Most Roma young people have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain university degree."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member, it is necessary to give broad awareness of these issues among both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the sooner the school begins a Gypsy student, the more likely it will be to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - Lívia Jaróka said.
