"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographs effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "are as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion were shared," observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the Oscar cousin and the grand jury's award to Cannes, which recounted the poetry of a provincial cinema and nostalgia by the way of living the cinema that might be lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of traders, speak clearly: over the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and most of the rooms in the main cities are to be paid: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffered by the closures are the first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 less cinemas, following by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these three Italian regions themselves have made the largest number of new methonic cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec," it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequentes are willing to transfer to the meticones.
